<dl id="s14037bf"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us14" href="#s14037bf">Oxen of the Sun: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s14all.htm#s14037bf">sector 37(bf)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ with some pleasantry <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="s14037bf"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/p/lexp.htm#s14037bf">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/p/p86.htm#s14037bf">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/p/p86.htm#s14037bf">1986 (14.998)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/p/l22p.htm#s14037bf">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#s14037bf">MS NLI.11A-4</ms> </li><li><a name="p11d" href="../udra/u14da.htm#p11d">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/p/p11d.htm#s14037bf">Draft: 14.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[from Gibbon, <cite>Decline and Fall</cite>:]</font> Constantius sat alone on a lofty car resplendent with gold and precious gems; and, except when he bowed his head to pass under the gates of the cities, he affected a stately demeanour of inflexible and <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> of insensible gravity <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Their repeated acclamations expressed their joy at beholding, after an absence of thirty-two years, the sacred person of the sovereign; and Constantius himself expressed, <mark>with some pleasantry</mark>, his affected surprise that the human race should thus suddenly be collected on the same spot. <small> George Saintsbury, <a name="GSAH" href="/udra/udex.htm#GSAH"><cite title="source">A History of English Prose Rhythm</cite></a> (1912), 282</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
